  "prompt": "Why are alkali metals very reactive?",
  "response": "Alkali metals (Group 1 elements: Li, Na, K, Rb, Cs, Fr) are highly reactive due to several key characteristics:\n\n1. Electronic configuration\n- They have only one valence electron in their outermost shell\n- This single electron is loosely held and easily removed\n- Losing this electron allows them to achieve a stable noble gas configuration\n\n2. Low ionization energy\n- The single valence electron requires very little energy to be removed\n- This makes them readily able to form positive ions (cations)\n\n3. Large atomic radius\n- Larger atomic size means the valence electron is further from the nucleus\n- Less attraction between the electron and nucleus makes it easier to remove\n\n4. Low electronegativity\n- They have weak attraction for electrons\n- Readily donate their valence electron in chemical reactions\n\n5. Reactivity trends\n- Reactivity increases down the group (from lithium to francium)\n- As atomic size increases, electron is further from nucleus and more easily removed\n\nTypical reactions include:\n- Reacting vigorously with water\n- Burning in oxygen\n- Forming ionic compounds easily\n- Reacting with halogens to form salts\n\nThese characteristics make alkali metals extremely reactive and require special handling.",
